  "text": "Apache Flink's windowing API provides a comprehensive extension mechanism for custom window assigners through a hierarchy of abstract base classes and interfaces.\n\n## WindowAssigner Base Class\nThe abstract `WindowAssigner` class (flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/WindowAssigner.java) is the foundation for all window assignment logic. Developers implementing custom window assigners must override four abstract methods:\n\n1. `Collection<W> assignWindows(T element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)` - Assigns zero or more windows to each element based on its timestamp and context.\n2. `Trigger<T, W> getDefaultTrigger()` - Provides the default trigger strategy for windows produced by this assigner.\n3. `TypeSerializer<W> getWindowSerializer(ExecutionConfig executionConfig)` - Returns a serializer for the window type to enable fault-tolerant state management.\n4. `boolean isEventTime()` - Indicates whether windows are assigned based on event time (true) or processing time (false).\n\n## MergingWindowAssigner Extension\nFor session-style windows that can merge overlapping windows, `MergingWindowAssigner` (flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/MergingWindowAssigner.java) extends `WindowAssigner` and adds the `void mergeWindows(Collection<W> windows, MergeCallback<W> callback)` method. This method enables custom merge logic through a callback interface that specifies which windows should be merged.\n\n## Trigger Lifecycle\nThe `Trigger` abstract base class (flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/triggers/Trigger.java) defines the lifecycle of window firing decisions with the following abstract methods:\n\n1. `TriggerResult onElement(T element, long timestamp, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Called when an element is added to a window pane to determine if evaluation should occur.\n2. `TriggerResult onProcessingTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Called when a processing-time timer fires.\n3. `TriggerResult onEventTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Called when an event-time timer fires.\n4. `void onMerge(W window, OnMergeContext ctx)` - Called when windows are merged (for stateful merge support).\n5. `void clear(W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Cleans up trigger state when a window is purged.\n\nAdditionally, `boolean canMerge()` allows triggers to declare merge capability.\n\n## Reference Implementation: EventTimeSessionWindows\n`EventTimeSessionWindows` (flink-streaming-java/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/EventTimeSessionWindows.java) demonstrates a complete implementation of `MergingWindowAssigner<Object, TimeWindow>`:\n\n- `assignWindows()` creates a single `TimeWindow` from the element's timestamp to timestamp + sessionTimeout.\n- `mergeWindows()` delegates to `TimeWindow.mergeWindows()`, which implements the merge logic by sorting windows and merging overlapping ones.\n- `getDefaultTrigger()` returns `EventTimeTrigger.create()`.\n- `isEventTime()` returns true since session windows are based on event time.\n\n## TimeWindow Class\nThe `TimeWindow` class (flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/TimeWindow.java) represents a time interval from start (inclusive) to end (exclusive). Key methods include:\n\n- Constructor: `TimeWindow(long start, long end)`\n- Accessors: `long getStart()` and `long getEnd()`\n- Utility methods: `boolean intersects(TimeWindow other)`, `TimeWindow cover(TimeWindow other)`, and `long maxTimestamp()`\n- Static merge utility: `static void mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergingWindowAssigner.MergeCallback<TimeWindow> c)` - Implements the merge algorithm used by session window assigners.\n\nThe class also includes an inner `Serializer` class that provides TypeSerializer implementation for state serialization.\n\nThis architecture enables developers to create custom window assigners by extending `WindowAssigner` (or `MergingWindowAssigner` for session-style semantics) and implementing the required abstract methods, providing complete control over window assignment, trigger behavior, and state management."
}

